Now let's see a visual of a pairplot between 3 variables

In [14]:
sns.pairplot(data[['Price', 'Power_bhp', 'Engine_CC']]);

Visualization hopefully must have given you a little better idea than the tables above

Takeaway points:¶

  • As humans, we cannot interpret the dataset with just having a glance at the large tables of values.
  • Summary statistics (mean, standard deviations, median, etc) are a little better tools for understanding the data.
  • However, fun fact: We can have two datasets having same means, same variance and same correlations, yet being totally completely different. Check out this fun blog!
  • Bascially, humans are good visual learners. And therefore, visualizations are an important tool to get an initial feel for your dataset.

Univariate Explorations¶

  • In this section, we will learn about visualizing "one feature" at a time.
  • These are highly dependent on the data type for which you need a plot.
  • Univariate explorations are one of the starting points of Data Visualizations. They give you an idea about features themselves, without trying to understand their behavior with other features.

So let's dive into it!

Some things to note:¶

  • Always include the title, xlabel and ylabel for a plot.
  • Always end the cell with a ";" in cells in which your are writing commands for a plot. If you don't end with a ";", you can can unwanted text like the following:

What Happens if you don't end with ;¶

In [92]:

Out[92]:
Text(0,0.5,'Count')

Number of Bins:¶

  • Default number of bins are 10. You can vary them by passing an attribute "bins" to the plt or distplot functions.
  • Increasing the bins increases information but also increases noise. Decreasing the bins loses some information, but also have reduced noise. You will need to find an optimal number of bins by varying it and find which is appropriate for your data.
In [94]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=[12, 4])
ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 1)
ax.hist(data.Price, bins=5, color=red2);
ax.set_title('Less bins')

ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 2)
ax.hist(data.Price, bins=500, color=blue3);
ax.set_title('More bins');

Case 2: Categorical Numerical Data (Bar graph)¶

Navigate Down

Bar Plot (Basic)¶

In [36]:
# Fuel Type: Categorical feature
sns.countplot(data=data, x='Fuel_Type')
plt.title('Fuel Type Distribution');

Some problems in above graph:¶

  • Use of colors: By default, a countplot uses a different color for each of the categories involved in the given feature. It might look fancy and beatiful to some, but an important question to ask is: Is it required? No!. Imagine this: The x axis already lists the different categories of plot (i.e CNG, Diesel, Petrol, etc). But we still are using a different color scheme for each. Rule of thumb: For every color introduced in the plot, you will also need to include the legend describing the meaning of those colors. Here, the introduction of legends would be redundant. Because, the x-axis is already doing that job. In general, try to plot your graphs as much as possible in unicolor.

  • The order of bars: Because we are dealing with nominal data, the order of the categories do not matter. So, we have the liberty to change the order by default. Quick question: What do you think would be a good ordering scheme here?

Check the next sub-slide to check out an improved version of the plot

Bar Graph: Standard Practice¶

In [42]:
# Bar chart: improved version
ordering = data['Fuel_Type'].value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).index
sns.countplot(data=data, x='Fuel_Type', order=ordering, color=blue3)
plt.title('Fuel Type Distribution - Improved Plot');

Univariate Explorations¶

Case 3: Discrete Data (Histogram with bin edges and width)¶

Navigate Down

  • If you want to plot a discrete quantitative variable, it is possible to select either a histogram or a bar chart to depict the data.
  • The histogram is the most immediate choice since the data is numeric, but there's one particular consideration to make regarding the bin edges. Since data points fall on set values, it can help to reduce ambiguity by putting bin edges between the actual values taken by the data.

Bar Graph on Discrete feature¶

In [58]:
# Seats Feature: What is we plot a Bar Chart?
sns.countplot(data=data, x='Seats', color=green1);
plt.title('Distribution of Seats - Bar Graph');

Looks good enough! But there's a problem. Imagine if we had cars with all seats vales as: 1, 3, 5, 6. In such a case, the countplot would just plot with x labels having 1,3,5 and 6. It won't consider 2 and 4. Which is a wrong practice!

Note: Missing values were replaces with -1 previously while cleaning.

Using Histogram for Discrete Feature¶

In [60]:
# Stats Feature: Histogram
plt.hist(data.Seats, color=green3)
plt.title('Distribution of Seats - Histogram');

Problems:

  • It seems as if the variables are continous (than discrete)
  • The xlabels edges seem to be not matching

Histogram for Discrete Feature: Standard Practice¶

In [69]:
# Seats Feature: How to plot a discerete variable?
ticks = np.arange(data.Seats.min(), data.Seats.max(), 1)
bin_edges = np.arange(data.Seats.min()-0.5, data.Seats.max()+0.5, 1)
plt.hist(data.Seats, color=green3, rwidth=0.8, bins=bin_edges)
plt.title('Distribution of Seats - Histogram (Improved)');
plt.xticks(ticks);

Check the correct version on next subslide

Bar Graph on Ordinal Feature: Standard Practice¶

In [72]:
# Owner_Type Feature
sns.countplot(data=data, x='Owner_Type', color=blue3, order=['First', 'Second', 'Third', 'Fourth & Above'])
plt.title('Distribution of Owner Types - Ordered');
  • Always order your axis correctly with the actual ordinality.
  • Here the graphs are naturaly decreasing order with their ordinality. But sometimes they might not. (e.g Count of Second > Third > First > Fourth & Above).
  • In categorical nominal data, we could arrange the order on the basis of the decreasing count (there existed no particular order), but here WE SHOULD NOT!

  • Numerical Discrete: Histogram with width and bin edges
  • Categorical Ordinal: Bar Graph with order

Case 1: Numerical vs Numerical¶

Navigate Down

Scatterplot¶

If we want to inspect the relationship between two numeric variables, the standard choice of plot is the scatterplot.

In [76]:
sns.scatterplot(data=data, x='Power_bhp', y='Price', color=red2)
plt.title('Effect of Engine Power on Price');

Alternative Approach: Regplot¶

In [78]:
sns.regplot(data=data, x='Power_bhp', y='Price', color=red2, fit_reg=True)
plt.title('Effect of Engine Power on Price');

Log Transform¶

Sometimes having a log transform on one variable can capture better pattern

In [221]:
def log_trans(x, inverse = False):     
    if not inverse:         
        return np.log10(x)     
    else:         
        return np.power(10, x) 
 
sns.regplot(data['Power_bhp'], data['Price'].apply(log_trans)) 
tick_locs = [10, 20, 50, 100, 200, 500] 
plt.yticks(log_trans(tick_locs), tick_locs);
plt.ylabel('log of Price');

In Above Plot:¶

At lower values, log of Price seems to have a good linear relation with Power_bhp

By the way, did you notice the clutter in the graph? Well that's the next thing we will address - Overplotting

Overplotting - Overplotting, Transparency, and Jitter¶

If we have a very large number of points to plot OR our numeric variables are discrete-valued, then it is possible that using a scatterplot straightforwardly will not be informative. The visualization will suffer from overplotting, where the high amount of overlap in points makes it difficult to see the actual relationship between the plotted variables.

Check out the next subslide to understand the issues

Examples of Overplotting?¶

Having discrete numerical values¶

In [150]:
sns.regplot(data=data, x='Year', y='Seats', color=red2, fit_reg=False)
plt.title('Seats and Year - Having Discrete values ');

Having too many values¶

In [111]:
sns.regplot(data=data, x='Price', y='Kilometers_Driven', color=blue3, fit_reg=False)
plt.title('Kilometers Driven and Price - Having too many values ');
plt.ylim(-1, 300000);

Adding Transperacy¶

  • Transparency can be added to a scatter call by adding the "alpha" parameter set to a value between 0 (fully transparent, not visible) and 1 (fully opaque).
  • Where more points overlap, the darker the image will be. Here, we can now see that there is a moderate negative relationship between the two numeric variables. Values of 0 and 10 on the x-axis are much rarer than the central values.
In [116]:
# Adding some transperacy
sns.regplot(data=data, x='Year', y='Seats', color=red2, fit_reg=False, scatter_kws = {'alpha' : 1/3})
plt.title('Seats and Year - Having Discrete values ');

Adding Jitter¶

  • As an alternative or companion to transparency, we can also add jitter to move the position of each point slightly from its true value.
  • The jitter settings will cause each point to be plotted in a uniform 0.1 (e.g below) range of their true values
In [151]:
# Adding some transperacy and jitter
sns.regplot(data=data, x='Year', y='Seats', color=red2, fit_reg=False, 
            x_jitter=0.1, y_jitter=0.1, scatter_kws = {'alpha' : 1/2})
plt.title('Seats and Year - Having Discrete values ');

Basically, whenever you have a bad scatterplot, try varying transperacy and jitter

Three Options:¶

1. Clustered Bar Graph¶

In [179]:
# Location and Fuel Type
sns.countplot(data=data, x='Location', hue='Fuel_Type');

See better plot on next slide

In [185]:
plt.figure(figsize=[15, 8])
sns.countplot(data=data, y='Location', hue='Fuel_Type', order = data.Location.value_counts().index,
              hue_order = data.groupby('Fuel_Type')['Price'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).index,
             palette=[blue1, red2, green3, 'darkorange'])
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.title('Fuels types in different cities');

That brings us to another interesting concept:

Color Palette¶

3 types of color Palettes:¶

  • Categorical Color Palettes: When used for nominal variables
  • Sequential Color Palettes: When used for ordinal or discrete variables
  • Diverging COlor Palettes: Also used for ordinal or disrete, but where the values are having both positive and negative trends.

Please read this before proceeding.

P.S: We used a categorical color palette in the above plot

Sequential Color Palette Example¶

In [190]:
plt.figure(figsize=[10, 5])
sns.countplot(data=data, x='Fuel_Type', hue='Owner_Type', order = data.Fuel_Type.value_counts().index,
              hue_order = ['First', 'Second', 'Third', 'Fourth & Above'],
             palette=sns.cubehelix_palette(4))
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.title('Owner Types in each Fuel type');

2. Heatmaps¶

Sometimes Heatmaps are a good alternative to Clustered Bar Graphs (specially, where clustered bar charts can become clumsy in case of lots of categorical variables)

In [193]:
plt.figure(figsize=[15, 7])
sns.heatmap(pd.crosstab(data.Location, data.Brand), annot=True, fmt="d");
sns.color_palette("BuGn_r")
plt.title('Types of Brand, Location wise');

For heatmap above:¶

  • annot means, whether to print actual value counts
  • fmt ="d" means print values in integer form
  • Colro palette taken from here
  • More about Heatmap parameters can be found here

3. Faceting¶

  • Faceting can almost work for any multivariate plot if there is a categorical variable involved.
  • Bascially it creates seperate subplots for each category and then individual univarate plots in each one of them.
In [204]:
g = sns.FacetGrid(data=data, col='Owner_Type')
g.map(sns.countplot, 'Fuel_Type', color=green3)
g.set_titles('Fuel type in {col_name} owner type');

Extra: 3-variate plot using Faceting¶

  • Faceted by Transmission type
  • In each FacetGrid, a Categorical (Fuel Type) vs Numerical (Price) barplot
In [206]:
g = sns.FacetGrid(data=data, col='Transmission', size=4)
g.map(sns.barplot,'Fuel_Type','Price', color=green1);

Bascially, you can do multi-variate explorations easily by Faceting More will be taught ahead!

1. Box Plot¶

sns.boxplot(data=data, x='Fuel_Type', y='Mileage_Value')

Many problems in the above plot. Hopefully, you would've figured out Check next subslide

Good Practice for Box Plots¶

In [210]:
ordering = data.groupby('Fuel_Type')['Mileage_Value'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).index
sns.boxplot(data=data, x='Fuel_Type', y='Mileage_Value', color=green3,
           order = ordering)
plt.title('Mileage value in each Fuel Type - Improved Plot');

Shifting Axes possible¶

In [214]:
ordering = data.groupby('Fuel_Type')['Mileage_Value'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).index
sns.boxplot(data=data, y='Fuel_Type', x='Mileage_Value', color=blue1,
           order = ordering)
plt.title('Mileage value in each Fuel Type - Improved Plot');

2. Violin Plot¶

Exactly same syntax as Box Plots. Just replace "boxplot" by "violinplot"

In [216]:
ordering = data.groupby('Fuel_Type')['Mileage_Value'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).index
sns.violinplot(data=data, x='Fuel_Type', y='Mileage_Value', color=green3,
           order = ordering)
plt.title('Mileage value in each Fuel Type - Violin Plot');

3. Bar Plot¶

Same syntax as boxplot. Just replace "boxplot" by "barplot"

In [217]:
ordering = data.groupby('Fuel_Type')['Mileage_Value'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).index
sns.barplot(data=data, x='Fuel_Type', y='Mileage_Value', color=green3,
           order = ordering)
plt.title('Mileage value in each Fuel Type - Violin Plot');

Important Question: What is the difference between Bar Plot and Box/Violin Plot?

  • Box/Violin Plots convey the 5 number summary statistics (min, Q1, median, Q3, max) on alternate axis.
  • While, Barplot showcases Mean and Standard deviation on alternate axis.
  • Generally, 5 number summary are preferred (because they are robust). However, barplots give a larger interpretability.

Another Example¶

In [218]:
sns.barplot(data=data, x='Location', y='Price', color=blue3,
           order = data.groupby('Location')['Price'].mean().sort_values(ascending=False).index)

plt.xticks(rotation=90);
